# REST conventions
- Plural nouns for resources (`/submissions`, `/appeals`), nested no more than one level
  (`/admin/verdicts/:id/override`, not deeper).
- Correct status codes: 201 on create, 200 on read/update, 204 on delete with no body, 400 for
  validation failure, 401 for missing/invalid auth, 403 for authenticated-but-insufficient-role,
  404 for not-found-or-not-yours (see security.mdc on ownership leaks).
- One consistent error response shape across every endpoint (Nest's default
  `{ statusCode, message, error }` is fine — don't invent a bespoke shape per controller).
- List endpoints (`GET /submissions`, `GET /admin/verdicts`) support pagination params and return a
  total count alongside the page of results — don't return an unbounded array as the project grows.
- Add `@ApiOperation` / `@ApiResponse` Swagger decorators on every endpoint. It's close to free in
  Nest and gives you working API docs as a deliverable with almost no extra effort.

# Testing
- The verdict-precedence function (PROJECT_PLAN.md 3.5) and the policy-snapshot-embedding logic (3.1)
  are pure, deterministic, and get unit tests with no mocking required — there's no excuse to skip
  these, they're the cheapest tests in the whole app and cover the most heavily-graded logic.
- Any test touching the submission flow mocks the moderation engine — never make a real Groq API call
  from a test run.
- At minimum one end-to-end test covering the full loop: submit → verdict produced → appeal filed →
  admin resolves → verdict updated.
- All tests run via a single `npm test` command and must pass before a build phase is considered done.
